{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625478"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:25:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:25:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17027"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17027"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.02,0.14,0.67,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9717"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69008"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9717"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17027"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54465"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4938"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5202"},{"type":"tags","id":"5221"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22864"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22903"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69008"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical student asks about the pharmacokinetic properties of buprenorphine that make it useful for treating opioid dependence.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pharmacokinetic properties of buprenorphine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Low lipid solubility with high oral bioavailability","Short half-life requiring frequent dosing","Rapid dissociation from opioid receptors","Long half-life with high sublingual absorption","Moderate half-life with low receptor affinity"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBuprenorphine has a \u003Cstrong\u003Elong half-life with high sublingual absorption\u003C/strong\u003E. The half-life ranges from 24-60 hours, allowing for once-daily dosing in opioid dependence treatment. Its high lipid solubility enables effective sublingual administration, bypassing first-pass metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow lipid solubility with high oral bioavailability\u003C/strong\u003E: buprenorphine actually has high lipid solubility and undergoes extensive first-pass metabolism, resulting in poor oral bioavailability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShort half-life requiring frequent dosing\u003C/strong\u003E: buprenorphine has a long half-life of 24-60 hours, which is advantageous for maintenance therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid dissociation from opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E: buprenorphine exhibits slow dissociation kinetics from opioid receptors, which contributes to its prolonged therapeutic effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EModerate half-life with low receptor affinity\u003C/strong\u003E: buprenorphine demonstrates both a long half-life and exceptionally high receptor affinity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese pharmacokinetic properties make buprenorphine particularly suitable for opioid dependence treatment, as the long duration of action provides stable blood levels and reduces the frequency of dosing required.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Buprenorphine has a long half-life of 24-60 hours, making it suitable for once-daily dosing.","Buprenorphine can be administered sublingually due to its high lipid solubility but has poor oral bioavailability.","The high potency and slow dissociation from receptors contributes to buprenorphine\u0027s long duration of action."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54465"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17027"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54465"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T19:57:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T10:16:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9717"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69008"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://a